[ssm/design/source-artifact-contract] Design source descriptor-to-artifact contract (complete)
The physical sources.json ledger is generic; every caller enters through the
single access boundary designed in ssm/design/ledger-access-boundary. This
contract governs only docs sources registered through Scout's source-management
commands: each retains the fixed declaration together with fetched state; there
is no separate descriptor entity and no additional public source fields. Every
managed docs source resolves
deterministically to the docs corpus and an artifact root beneath
resources/<safe-name>; ssm/design/source-artifact-path owns the safe-name
derivation and any path move semantics. Its required mime names the expected
content representation; it is neither a transport protocol nor the independent
chunk-adapter kind introduced in ssm/design/chunk-adapters. Scout only fetches
HTTPS origins. Each caller-provided origin is one source: Scout may follow its
permitted redirects but stages only that final response as one artifact. It
never treats a response as a catalog, follows links from it, or expands one
source into additional sources.
The fetcher returns a successful result only after staging a validated candidate
manifest with its artifact path, byte count, SHA-256, observed MIME, and final
URL. A staged candidate is not a live source snapshot and cannot be discovered
by a corpus or returned by search. Failure is a separate attempt outcome and
cannot masquerade as either a staged candidate or a live snapshot. This
contract is consumed by the ledger, lifecycle, admission, and command-surface
designs.
Accept: the owner confirms how every registered source resolves to one corpus,
one artifact location, and one fetch-result shape.
> The fixed declared row is name, origin URL, mime, and ttl_days; mime is the expected media type.
> Scout admits HTTPS origins only; transport is not encoded in mime.
> Every managed docs source belongs to the docs corpus and materializes beneath resources/<safe-name>; the safe-name mapping and path move semantics are settled by ssm/design/source-artifact-path.
> One caller-provided URL is one source and stages one final response artifact; no catalog expansion, link discovery, crawl, or vendor-specific fan-out exists.
> A successful fetch returns a validated staged candidate manifest: artifact path, bytes, SHA-256, observed MIME, and final URL; a candidate is not query-visible.
> Failure is separate from a staged candidate and a live snapshot.
> Chunk kind is a separate local indexing concern and never reuses the source mime field.
---
[ssm/design/ledger-access-boundary] Design authoritative ledger access boundary (complete)
resources/sources.json is one generic source ledger. Every current and future
caller uses the same authoritative physical-ledger access boundary; no source
category has a separate writer, lock, journal, or recovery protocol. The owner
has settled this operation-level contract: an add applies directly through the
locked atomic-write path; an update or remove first durably records its intent,
then atomically applies it; and every later ledger access completes a pending
update/remove before serving the caller. The approved physical representation
is a sibling intent journal beside sources.json: sources.json remains the last
committed readable ledger, while the journal is the separately durable,
recoverable pending update/remove instruction. Every access locks the pair,
resolves a present journal before serving the caller, and deletes the journal
only after the ledger reflects its requested result. This decision does not
select batch commit semantics; the journal may carry the batch intent settled
in ssm/design/batch-atomicity. This task also owns migration of current direct
freshness.stamp-style writers onto that one API. It owns only generic
persistence access, not each caller's source declaration or corpus semantics.
Accept: the approved sibling-journal boundary gives all callers direct atomic
add or replayable update/remove as appropriate, and no two independently
implemented writers can mutate the physical ledger or bypass its recovery
protocol.
> sources.json remains one generic source ledger.
> Every ledger writer uses one authoritative access and recovery boundary.
> Adds apply directly through a locked atomic write.
> Updates and removes durably record intent before atomic application; a later ledger access completes an interrupted operation.
> Intent storage is a sibling journal: sources.json is committed data; the journal is a pending update/remove instruction.
> Every access locks and resolves a present journal before serving a caller; it deletes the journal only after applying its requested result.
---
[ssm/design/source-registry] Design the source ledger and its CRUD operations (notstarted)
Redefine the docs source registry as a single ledger -- sources.json's existing
fetched-state role absorbs the registry too; there is no separate descriptor
entity. Physical access to that generic ledger is settled by
ssm/design/ledger-access-boundary. Each docs record retains the fixed declared
row: name, origin URL, required
mime (the expected content media type), ttl_days, plus either no live snapshot
or exactly one committed live snapshot. A candidate, partial artifact,
in-progress fetch, or index-not-yet-published artifact is not a representable
live source state. Freshness is derived from a committed snapshot's timestamp,
not stored as a mutable source-state flag. HTTPS transport and the local chunk
kind are separate concerns; there is no default protocol value in the declared
row and no per-source fetch-strategy field. Callers operate on the ledger via CRUD: one call carries a
batch of rows, each tagged add/update/remove. A mutation record distinguishes
the existing source target from its desired declaration: an add supplies a
desired origin URL, an origin-changing update needs both a target and a
replacement declaration, and a remove names only its target. The owner decides
the stable target identity, whether the declared name is that identity, and
collision/rename rules. Each row identifies exactly one source and receives
exactly one outcome record; no row discovers, creates, or fetches another
source. A caller-provided desired origin URL remains one declaration, never a
fan-out mechanism.
ssm/design/batch-atomicity owns whether row mutations commit independently or
as one batch. The ledger stays small by design -- every access reads and locks
the whole file, no partial or indexed access.
Add rows apply directly as source registration, not as a claim that their
artifact has fetched or their index has published; ssm/design/source-lifecycle
owns those later states. The generic ledger-access boundary applies its
crash-safe two-step update/remove protocol: it durably records a mutation
intent before resolving it through the publication boundary. Recovery never
directly deletes or replaces a reader-visible source row: it completes the
pending mutation through the same publication/removal transaction until the
declaration, live snapshot, and docs index agree. An interruption leaves the
intent behind, so the operation always completes on the next access instead of
landing half-done.
The durable intent needs a representation that stays readable and recoverable
on every access; a raw append to a standalone JSON object cannot itself be
that representation. The intent/recovery journal is separate from the live
snapshot record and cannot point readers at a candidate. The settled generic
ledger-access boundary owns all physical writer migration, locking, and
recovery; this task consumes it to define docs records and mutations. Define
source identity and batch semantics too: duplicate names, divergent same-name
adds, stale re-adds, target/declaration distinction, and row-operation
ordering; batch commit semantics belong only to ssm/design/batch-atomicity.
Deterministic mapping from that identity to an artifact path, including path
collision and rename/move semantics, belongs only to
ssm/design/source-artifact-path.
Needs failure/timeout configuration (lock-wait duration, retry policy) for
ledger access -- see ssm/design/scout-config. Freshness selection must be a
structured result shared by refresh and warning presentation, not a refresh
parser for user-facing warning strings.
-> ssm/design/ledger-access-boundary
-> ssm/design/scout-config
-> ssm/design/source-artifact-contract
-> ssm/design/source-publication-boundary
