[ssm/design/source-publication-boundary] Design the source publication boundary (complete)
The approved reader model is a docs-only master publication pointer. It names
one immutable publication generation that binds the docs source-state snapshot,
one live artifact generation or no snapshot per source, and the corresponding
docs-index generation. Every docs reader resolves this master pointer first;
sources.json remains the generic mutation/recovery ledger and is not an
independent docs-query truth. A descriptor update is not reader-visible until
its candidate artifact and index membership are ready; removal is not reader-
visible until its old membership is absent. The ledger mutation journal may
record a desired change, but replay must route through this boundary rather
than directly replacing or deleting a reader-visible row.

Candidate generations are immutable and unreachable until the master pointer
changes. The initial cut retains prior complete generations conservatively;
cleanup is not a publication prerequisite. A missing, malformed, or internally
inconsistent master publication is control-plane-fatal rather than a reason to
scan sibling artifacts or index generations for a plausible fallback.

The physical boundary is `resources/.docs-publications/`: `CURRENT` contains
one opaque publication id, atomically replaced only after its immutable
`generations/<id>/manifest.json` is fully written and flushed. A manifest is
self-contained: schema version, publication id, parent id, the complete
reader-visible docs source-state snapshot keyed by source identity, one
generation-qualified artifact reference and digest or no-snapshot state per
source, and the referenced docs-index generation and digest. The master
publication pointer is the only docs reader entrypoint. A docs index generation
may remain stored beneath `.index/docs/`, but `.index/docs/CURRENT` is neither
written nor read as an independent docs publication truth.

Each candidate names the master publication from which it was staged.
Fetching, artifact staging, and index construction occur outside the short
publication commit lock. Under that lock, a candidate whose base is still
current publishes by atomically flipping the master pointer. If another
publication won first, the control plane automatically rebases the already-
staged source mutation onto the newer complete publication, builds the
necessary next index generation outside the lock, and retries commit until it
publishes. Rebase contention never discards a valid staged mutation; a process
interruption leaves the ledger intent pending, and a later ledger access
resumes the same rebase procedure. Only an invalid candidate artifact, index,
or manifest is source/control-plane-fatal as applicable.
Accept: after an interruption at any point, a reader can resolve only the
prior declaration with its prior snapshot and index membership, or the next
complete set, never a new declaration with old results or a removed declaration
with retained results.
-> ssm/design/source-artifact-contract
> Docs readers resolve one master publication pointer, not raw sources.json, artifact roots, and docs index CURRENT independently.
> One immutable publication generation binds the docs source-state snapshot, artifact generations, and docs-index generation.
> Candidate generations are unreachable until publication; initial cleanup retains prior complete generations conservatively.
> An invalid master publication is control-plane-fatal; readers never infer a fallback by scanning sibling generations.
> A stale staged candidate automatically rebases its source mutation onto the latest complete publication before retrying the short commit.
> `resources/.docs-publications/CURRENT` atomically names one immutable, self-contained generation manifest; it is the only docs reader entrypoint.
> Publication rebase continues until commit; interruption preserves the ledger intent so a later access resumes rather than abandons the valid staged mutation.
