[ssm/design/source-lifecycle] Design source live-snapshot publication lifecycle (notstarted)
Apply the state-space entropy ladder to artifact and index publication. A
registered source has only two query-visible states: no live snapshot, or one
committed live snapshot. A live snapshot is introduced only by a complete
publication that includes its validated artifact and makes it searchable; the
representation has no live variant for partial bytes, a staged candidate, an
unindexed artifact, or an index entry without its artifact. Candidates remain
outside corpus discovery and query-visible indexes until that publication.

An explicit re-fetch or refresh creates a separate attempt, never a mutation
of the current live snapshot. Failure or interruption leaves the prior live
snapshot unchanged when one exists; for a source with no prior snapshot it
leaves no live snapshot. For refresh selection, a registered source with no
live snapshot is structurally absent regardless of TTL and is eligible for
refresh-stale. A failed refresh with a usable prior snapshot produces a
non-live attempt diagnostic record; ssm/design/attempt-diagnostics owns its
storage, lifetime, and clearing behavior. It cannot become a query-visible
source state. Removal commits to no live snapshot only when the source is no
longer queryable. The owner decides the concrete
state transition and outcome projection using the concrete publication boundary
settled in ssm/design/source-publication-boundary. This task does not choose a
second transaction mechanism; every reader must observe either the prior
complete publication or the next complete publication, never a cross-artifact
mixture.
Diagnostics are a read-time projection of this resolution, not a third stored
source state: stale content or a failed refresh with a usable prior snapshot is
a warning; no resolvable valid snapshot or failed snapshot-integrity validation
is source-fatal and returns no result from that source; inability to validate
the ledger, config, or publication boundary is control-plane-fatal and refuses
docs-corpus results rather than presenting ungrounded material as healthy.
Accept: the owner confirms a transition and diagnostic matrix in which reader
resolution admits only the prior committed snapshot or no snapshot, never a
partial, candidate, unindexed, or artifact/index-mismatched source. The
downstream verification task proves that matrix under deterministic failures.
-> ssm/design/fresh-source-refetch
-> ssm/design/source-publication-boundary
-> ssm/design/source-registry
---
[ssm/design/attempt-diagnostics] Design non-live fetch-attempt diagnostics (notstarted)
A failed refresh with a valid prior snapshot must remain visible as a warning
on later docs queries, but failures are not source snapshot states. Given the
ledger and lifecycle contracts, design the non-live attempt record: its binding
to a source and committed snapshot, durable location, retention, recovery, and
the exact event that clears or supersedes it. The record must not make a
candidate, failed attempt, or partial artifact discoverable as a live source.
Accept: the owner confirms how a failed refresh warning survives long enough
to be actionable, then clears or changes only through an unambiguous later
attempt outcome without changing the visible snapshot prematurely.
-> ssm/design/source-lifecycle
-> ssm/design/source-registry
---
[ssm/design/source-hit-provenance] Design source-to-hit provenance and filtering (notstarted)
Given the source publication lifecycle, define the stable binding carried by
each docs-index chunk and search hit: source identity plus the committed
snapshot generation or manifest identity that produced it. At read time,
resolve that binding against the current publication boundary before a hit can
be returned. A hit whose source is absent, whose generation is not current, or
whose snapshot integrity cannot validate is excluded before ranking/output;
the structured diagnostic then distinguishes source-fatal from
control-plane-fatal. The owner decides the exact index metadata/id shape and
reader validation path without weakening source-specific suppression in the
shared docs corpus. That validation is invoked by every public docs-query
entry point, including normal CLI, JSON CLI, and the resident worker used by
MCP; no route may format or return unvalidated docs hits.
The binding occupies the canonical adapter tag envelope alongside `citation`;
the query path hydrates those tags from the loaded index generation before
filtering, ranking, or formatting. There is no second provenance sidecar or
reader-time inference from index ids/artifact paths.
Accept: an orphaned, stale-generation, or integrity-invalid fixture cannot
appear in docs-search output, while a valid source in the same corpus remains
searchable.
-> ssm/design/chunk-adapters
-> ssm/design/source-lifecycle
---
[ssm/design/source-diagnostics] Design actionable source-health diagnostics (notstarted)
Given the source live-snapshot publication model, design the structured
diagnostic contract consumed by batch commands and docs search. The diagnostic
is external to the source-state representation and contains at least severity,
scope, stable error code, affected source when applicable, and a settled public
repair action. FATAL diagnostics appear ahead of any response content and are
never collapsed into a generic freshness warning or parsed back from display
text. Source-fatal means the affected source cannot contribute results;
control-plane-fatal means docs search refuses corpus results until integrity is
re-established. WARN preserves results from a valid prior snapshot while
showing a stale or failed-refresh condition and its repair action. A
failed-refresh warning derives from the settled non-live attempt record, not a
mutable snapshot-state flag.
Accept: the owner confirms the public diagnostic payload and repair paths for
source-fatal, control-plane-fatal, and warning conditions on CLI, MCP, and
docs-search surfaces.
-> ssm/design/attempt-diagnostics
-> ssm/design/source-hit-provenance
-> ssm/design/source-lifecycle
---
[ssm/design/fetch-admission] Design remote fetch admission and resource policy (complete)
Given the source descriptor-to-artifact contract, decide the rules enforced
before Scout fetches a caller-supplied remote origin. HTTPS is the only
accepted scheme. Redirects are limited to five and every target must retain
both HTTPS and the origin's host. The declared and observed base MIME types
must match and be either `text/plain` or `text/markdown`; an absent charset is
UTF-8 and an explicit charset must be UTF-8. Any MIME/charset mismatch,
unsupported MIME, or invalid UTF-8 response fails before candidate staging. The
owner has chosen the resource values: 60 seconds per request and 80 MiB per
response. One source stages exactly one final response artifact, so a separate
aggregate source-byte cap or file cap would duplicate the response bound or
imply prohibited fan-out. Those values, plus the redirect-count limit, are
checked-in Scout configuration; scheme/MIME/charset policy remains fixed. This
task owns enforcement policy. One shared bounded staging writer checks any
declared response length when available, counts streamed response bytes, and
removes the incomplete staging area on a limit breach. Command-surface design
only decides how callers supply a row and receive a rejected or failed outcome.
The settled policy must be usable by the shared control plane for both CLI and
MCP calls.
Accept: the owner confirms the admission and resource contract, including how
each refused or exceeded limit is reported without claiming a lifecycle stage
that was not reached.
-> ssm/design/mime-representation
-> ssm/design/source-artifact-contract
> HTTPS is the only accepted origin scheme.
> Follow at most five redirects only when every redirect target remains HTTPS and has the original host.
> Require matching declared/observed text/plain or text/markdown MIME and UTF-8 charset; reject a mismatch before candidate staging.
> Scheme and MIME rules are fixed; request timeout, redirect count, and response-byte cap live in checked-in Scout config.
> One shared bounded staging writer enforces the configured response-byte limit, then removes incomplete staging on failure.
> The initial docs profile is 60 seconds per request and 80 MiB per response.
