[ssm/design/scout-config] Design where scout's own operational config lives (complete)
Scout operational configuration lives in checked-in `resources/scout.json`,
separate from the generic source data in `sources.json`. `resources/config.py`
loads it once through a strict schema: a missing, malformed, unknown-key, or
wrong-type configuration is control-plane-fatal rather than silently defaulted.
The source control plane, search worker, and CLI/MCP wrappers consume the same
parsed configuration; environment variables do not override these operational
values.

The initial schema is intentionally small: `schema_version: 1`; ledger
`lock_wait_seconds: 30` and `lock_poll_milliseconds: 100`; fetch
`request_timeout_seconds: 60`, `max_redirects: 5`, and
`max_response_bytes: 83886080`. On lock contention, poll only until the
configured wait expires, then return an explicit `LEDGER_BUSY` diagnostic with
a retry repair action. Do not retry a completed/mid-flight mutation under a new
operation: journal recovery completes pending update/remove work on the next
ledger access. This config applies uniformly to every generic ledger client.
Accept: one checked-in strict configuration source supplies all settled ledger
access and fetch admission knobs; invalid config or exhausted lock wait fails
loudly without an environment/hardcoded fallback.
-> ssm/design/fetch-admission
-> ssm/design/ledger-access-boundary
> Config path: resources/scout.json; strict parser module: resources/config.py.
> Initial ledger policy: 30-second wait, 100-millisecond poll, then LEDGER_BUSY with retry action.
> Initial fetch policy: 60-second request timeout, 5 redirects, 80 MiB response cap.
> No environment override or silent default for checked-in operational configuration.
